<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Projects | Alan Bagel</title>
  <meta
    name="description"
    content="Projects by Alan Bagel - games, compilers, terminal apps, and web platforms across Rust, Scala, TypeScript, Python, and C."
  />
  <meta name="robots" content="index, follow" />
  <meta name="theme-color" content="#1b211b" />
  <link rel="canonical" href="https://alanthebagel.com/projects" />
  <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
  <meta property="og:title" content="Projects | Alan Bagel" />
  <meta
    property="og:description"
    content="Projects by Alan Bagel - games, compilers, terminal apps, and web platforms across Rust, Scala, TypeScript, Python, and C."
  />
  <meta property="og:locale" content="en_US" />
  <meta property="og:url" content="https://alanthebagel.com/projects" />

  <script type="application/ld+json"<% if (typeof cspNonce !== 'undefined' && cspNonce) { %> nonce="<%= cspNonce %>"<% } %>>
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://alanthebagel.com/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Projects", "item": "https://alanthebagel.com/projects" }
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/site.css?v=<%= assetVersion %>" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/vendor/lenis.css?v=<%= assetVersion %>" />
  <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="/images/favicon.png" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net" crossorigin />
  <link
    href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500;600;700;800&family=Manrope:wght@400;500;600;700&family=Sora:wght@500;600;700&display=swap"
    rel="stylesheet"
  />
  <link rel="prefetch" href="/" />
</head>
<body>
  <svg aria-hidden="true" style="position:absolute;width:0;height:0"><filter id="grain"><feTurbulence type="fractalNoise" baseFrequency="0.65" numOctaves="3" stitchTiles="stitch"/><feColorMatrix type="saturate" values="0"/></filter></svg>

  <main class="projects-page-main" role="main" aria-label="Projects content">
    <section class="projects-section" id="projects">
      <nav class="projects-topnav" aria-label="Site navigation">
        <a class="projects-topnav-home" href="/">Alan Bagel</a>
        <span class="projects-topnav-sep">/</span>
        <span class="projects-topnav-current">Projects</span>
        <span class="projects-topnav-sep">/</span>
        <a class="projects-topnav-link" href="/blog">Blog</a>
      </nav>

      <p class="section-label">Projects</p>

      <div class="projects-list">

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">01 / Featured</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">Microcosm</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A 2D roguelike in Pygame and OpenGL. Runs escalate through denser waves and
                tighter resource windows. I spent most of my time on two things: making combat
                feel responsive (clear telegraphs, tight hit feedback) and keeping frame pacing
                stable when there are 50+ entities on screen.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Enemy AI scales based on how far you've gotten, how long you've been alive, and how well you're playing.</li>
                <li>Combat runs on frame-precise timing: i-frames, telegraphed attacks, and collision that actually matches what you see.</li>
                <li>Heavy optimization work to keep fights smooth. Vectorized movement, aggressive culling, fast collision filtering.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Python</span>
                  <span class="tag">Pygame</span>
                  <span class="tag">OpenGL</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">2D Roguelike</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://alandabagel.itch.io/microcosm" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero">
            <img src="/images/acsl-academy.png" alt="ACSL Academy learn page showing lesson cards organized by contest" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">02</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">ACSL Academy</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                ACSL competition prep platform built with SvelteKit and Supabase. Lessons,
                practice problems, and timed contest sets. I built it because the study
                resources for ACSL were scattered and none of them tracked what you'd
                actually learned.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>30+ lessons covering core ACSL topics, ordered by difficulty so you're not jumping between easy and hard randomly.</li>
                <li>Timed practice sets that mimic the actual contest format.</li>
                <li>Progress tracking per account so you can see what's sticking and what needs more work.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">SvelteKit</span>
                  <span class="tag">Tailwind</span>
                  <span class="tag">Supabase</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Full-Stack Platform</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://acsl-academy.vercel.app" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">03</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">tiscord</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                Discord in your terminal. I wanted something I could keep in a tmux pane
                without burning 500MB of RAM on Electron. Connects directly to Discord's
                gateway over WebSocket, renders with Ratatui. Browse servers, send messages,
                react, search, see typing indicators. Images show up inline if your terminal
                supports Kitty or Sixel graphics.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Live gateway connection with message streaming and typing indicators. Tokens stored in OS keychain or an encrypted fallback file.</li>
                <li>Inline image rendering via Kitty graphics protocol, with Sixel as a fallback for older terminals.</li>
                <li>~12,600 lines of Rust. Three async tasks (gateway, actions, TUI) talking over channels so nothing blocks.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Rust</span>
                  <span class="tag">Ratatui</span>
                  <span class="tag">Crossterm</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Terminal Application</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/tiscord" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">04</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">algo</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                Write Python-like syntax, get C++17 out. I built this because writing C++
                under contest pressure is mostly fighting syntax, not solving the problem.
                The compiler only emits the stdlib functions your code actually uses, so the
                output is short enough to read and submit directly.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Full pipeline in Scala 3: lexer, parser, type checking, optimizer, codegen. Targets g++ -std=c++17 -O2.</li>
                <li>Built-in graphs (BFS, Dijkstra, Floyd, MST), segment trees, BIT, DSU. If you don't use them, they don't appear in the output.</li>
                <li>Test suite diffs compiler output against expected C++ files, then compiles the result to verify it's valid.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Scala 3</span>
                  <span class="tag">C++17</span>
                  <span class="tag">SBT</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Compiler</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/algo" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">05</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">Territory War</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                1v1 territory game. Both players move at the same time on a shared grid,
                leaving trails. Enclose an area to claim it. The AI has six distinct
                strategies and gets smarter about switching between them as levels progress.
                Every level is beatable with multiple loadouts so there's no single "correct" answer.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Six AI strategies (Greedy Expand, Wall, Encircle, Deny, Efficient Fill, Corner Trap) with per-strategy cooldowns.</li>
                <li>AI progression from random switching to counter-picking to anticipating your switches based on cooldown state.</li>
                <li>Every level validated to be winnable with at least 3 different player loadout combinations.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">TypeScript</span>
                  <span class="tag">esbuild</span>
                  <span class="tag">Vitest</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Strategy Game</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">In Progress</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/Territory-War" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">06</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">CalcGD</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                Geometry Dash on a TI-84 Plus CE. 320x240 screen, 256 colors, no floating
                point, 150KB of RAM. Jump physics use a lookup table instead of actual math.
                Collision detection reads pixel colors from the framebuffer. Includes a level
                editor and practice mode with checkpoints.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Jump and fly mechanics running on integer-only physics via pre-computed lookup tables.</li>
                <li>In-game level editor with custom .8xv file format. User levels work the same as built-in ones.</li>
                <li>Behind-sprite buffers for rendering because full double buffering would eat half the available RAM.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">C</span>
                  <span class="tag">CE Toolchain</span>
                  <span class="tag">Make</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Calculator Port</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/CalcGD" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">07 / Collaborative</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">Sauna</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                Browser-native game library. Play PC games without downloading anything. I
                worked on the frontend with a small team (SpirrTeam), starting from vanilla
                JS and migrating first to Svelte 5, then to TypeScript. The app has a custom
                window manager that mimics a desktop OS, offline caching, and play time tracking.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Custom window manager with drag, resize, and z-index stacking. Games launch in sandboxed iframes with pointer lock.</li>
                <li>Migrated the codebase twice: imperative DOM to Svelte 5 components, then JS to TypeScript with full linting.</li>
                <li>Works offline via service workers. Library state persists in localStorage and syncs when the backend comes back.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Svelte 5</span>
                  <span class="tag">TypeScript</span>
                  <span class="tag">Tailwind</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Web App (Team)</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/SpirrTeam/Sauna" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">08</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">The Legend of Rick</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                2D platformer in Godot. I've been spending most of my time on jump feel:
                the arcs, the momentum, how fast you recover after landing. The goal is
                controls that work the same whether you're doing precision jumps or fighting.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Jump physics tuned for consistency across precision platforming and combat sections.</li>
                <li>Multiple stage types with checkpoint flow and enemy timing that matches the movement speed.</li>
                <li>Boss encounters and pacing work in progress.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Godot</span>
                  <span class="tag">GDScript</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">2D Platformer</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">In Progress</p>
              </div>
              <span class="project-link muted">Coming soon</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <footer class="site-footer" aria-label="Site footer">
    <p class="site-footer-line">// &copy; <%= new Date().getFullYear() %> alan bagel. keep calm and eat bagels.</p>
  </footer>

  <script src="/js/utils.js?v=<%= assetVersion %>" defer></script>
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/gsap@3.14.2/dist/gsap.min.js" defer></script>
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/gsap@3.14.2/dist/ScrollTrigger.min.js" defer></script>
  <script src="/js/vendor/lenis.min.js?v=<%= assetVersion %>" defer></script>
  <script src="/js/projects.js?v=<%= assetVersion %>" defer></script>
</body>
</html>
